In our solar system these processes can be investigated in an exemplary way.
With the "Solar Orbiter" the Esa has already approved a mission of the M class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe should start in 2017 and observe the surface and activity of the sun closely.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and his moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa provides for the first of the three L missions of the Cosmic Vision programme.
The "Juice" probe (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
