And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be stabbed, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile calls during the flight continue to be forbidden.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may revoke the ban on certain electronic devices at start and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker from the National Transportation Safety Board, safety experts for national transport issues on CBS News said phones would still be considered a risk.
"Handy is really a problem, not only because they could cause potential disturbances in navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that the transmission from the air can also disturb broadcast masts," says Rosenker.
A consultative committee of the industry, set up by the FAA to investigate this issue, recommended last month that the government allow a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions for use.
Critics like the democratic senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri believe that there are no valid security reasons for the prohibition.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the equipment has become present.
In some studies it is mentioned that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the switching off of the device.
The FAA began in 1966 to restrict the use of electronic equipment by air travellers after reports of disturbances of navigation and communication equipment by passenger-led UKW radios, which at that time represented the latest technological trend.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also so designed and approved by the FAA that they do not care about electronic interference.
